    "summary": "Slovenia's independence from Yugoslavia was achieved through the Ten-Day War of June–July 1991, the shortest and least bloody conflict of the [[event:2696|Yugoslav Wars]]. Slovenia and Croatia simultaneously declared independence on June 25, 1991, and Yugoslav federal forces (JNA) moved to reassert control over Slovenia's borders and international airports. The Slovenian Territorial Defense forces mounted effective resistance, with guerrilla-style tactics and popular participation successfully containing the federal military.\n\nThe conflict ended relatively quickly for several reasons: Slovenia had a homogeneous population with virtually no Serb minority, making it strategically less important to Serbian nationalists who were focused on Croatia and Bosnia; the JNA suffered significant losses in materiel and morale; and European Community pressure mounted for a ceasefire. The Brioni Declaration of July 7 arranged a three-month suspension of the independence declaration, after which Slovenia's independence was recognized internationally. With EC recognition in January 1992, Slovenia had achieved independence at a cost of fewer than 70 lives. Slovenia subsequently joined the European Union and NATO in 2004, becoming the first former Yugoslav republic to join both organizations.",
